{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The aim of this chapter is to do this for a central topic in his metaphysics: his ontology of accidents.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "According to White, we conceive of the bodies we see around us in terms of the ten Aristotelian categories.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Are accidents beings in their own right, so that an inventory of what there is would include substances as well as various kinds of accidents? Or can accidents in some way be reduced to substances and their material parts?",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "According to White, many scholastic Aristotelians took the first route, and treated accidents as beings in their own right.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "To regiment this ontology, he proposed that at least some accidents could be reduced to substances and their material parts.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "But even though White aimed for a generally lean ontology of accidents, he did not believe that all accidents could be so reduced.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "As we will see, White believes that flawed accounts of location are a breeding ground for the dangerous hypothesis that God could have created, not one world, but many.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Given a correct account of location, however, this plurality of worlds hypothesis can be ruled out.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "White proposes a return to Aristotle: the location of an object is the inner surface limit of the body that contains it.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "According to White, a surrounding body that is in flux can remain constant with regard to some given point of reference.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Given such bodies and given minds to abstract away from motion, then, there is no need to add locations as separate items to an inventory of what there is.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "White, too, rejected the notion that accidents could behave like substances, and made it clear that no amount of theology could convince him of the reality of accidents detached from substances.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "According to White, the material substances we see around us are built up out of minute portions of the four elements, or atoms.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The specific way in which these atoms combine in a material substance determines which qualities it has.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Even though accidents never come without substances to bear them, and even though some accidents appear to reduce to substances, White believes that at least some accidents are distinct from their bearers.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "According to White, a change in the quantity of a material substance, or an increase or decrease of the area that it takes up, need not come with a change on the level of its atomic parts.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "The philosophy of Thomas White can be characterized as a systematic attempt to combine Aristotelian thought with the best of the new science of the early modern period.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Like modern thinkers such as Descartes, he criticizes scholastic tradition for treating accidents as entities in their own right over and above their bearers.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "At the same time, however, he does not think that all accidents can be accounted for in this way.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
