      "text": "White raises two main objections to the local modes account of location. The first is that, just as it is explanatorily vacuous to say that opium is sleep-inducing because it has a dormitive power, it is explanatorily vacuous to say that a substance is located in a location in virtue of its mode of location, or ubi.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "7": {
      "text": "The second objection is that the ubication theory flies in the face of our 'common notion' of location. According to White, science and philosophy ought to build upon the 'common notions' of ordinary men, not on the technical concepts of the learned few.",
